= Results and Discussion

This chapter should present the findings of your work, and discuss them in the context of your original aims and objectives. Present the data in an appropriate format (tables, charts, visualisations) and discuss what the data shows. You should link these results to your original objectives and discuss the extent to which they have been met, with clear evidence. At MSc level, results should be very well presented and clearly demonstrate the success of the project, with all original objectives met and supported by clear evidence.

== Data Analysis Approach

Briefly describe how the data was processed and analysed. This links back to the data analysis plan in the methodology chapter, and confirms the approach taken.

== Presentation of Results

Present your results clearly and systematically. Consider organising results by research question, hypothesis, or instrument, depending on what is most logical for your project.

=== Participant Demographics

If your project involved a user study, summarise the demographics of your participants (e.g., age, gender, experience level). This is typically presented as a table.

=== Quantitative Findings

Present any quantitative results, including statistical analyses. Use tables and charts to support the presentation. For each measure or instrument used, present the results and discuss their significance.

=== Qualitative Findings

If your project involved qualitative data collection (e.g., interviews, open-ended survey questions), present the results of your qualitative analysis here (e.g., thematic analysis, key themes and codes identified).
